The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Gujarat NRE Coke Ltd will issue bonus shares in the ratio of 1:1. The bonus was approved at the company?s recently held annual general meeting, Gujarat NRE has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. It has received the shareholders? nod to declare a 5 per cent final dividend, or 50 paise, on equity shares of Rs 10 each. An increase in the company?s authorised capital to Rs 1,500 crore from Rs 250 crore was also approved at the meeting. 

 LT Overseas has filed a draft red herring prospectus with the Securities and Exchange Board of India to enter the capital market with an initial public offering. The company proposes to offer 78,00,000 equity shares of Rs 10 each for cash at a premium, which will be decided through a book-building route. It will also allot 3,90,000 shares to its employees. 

 Small and medium businesses in India are set to invest up to $1.2 billion to beef up their Internet infrastructure and solutions this year, according to a recent study by New York-based AMI-Partners. 

 IBM and IIT Bombay have signed a memorandum of understanding to develop technology capabilities of common interest through collaborative research. The institutions will jointly develop technologies and capabilities in areas such as autonomic computing, grid computing, deep computing and databases. 

 Tricom India Ltd?s consolidated net profit stood at Rs 9.49 crore in 2005-06 against Rs 4.35 crore in the previous fiscal. Consolidated turnover was Rs 27.59 crore compared with Rs 14.5 crore in the previous year. The board has recommended a 20 per cent dividend on the increased paid-up capital of Rs 5.8 crore. 

 Hexaware Technologies has joined hands with Mu Sigma, a statistics and econometric services provider, to support its business intelligence and data warehousing capabilities.

